font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">In November 2000</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Wynn’s</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> subsidiary company Robert Wynn &amp; Sons Ltd</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> was awarded an £8.5m Freight Facilities grant by the Department for Transport. The grant represented 99</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">% of the total cost of the design and build of a specialist ro/ro barge and the purchase and conversion of a former inland tanker barge. The vessels, later named the Terra Marique and the Inland Navigator, work as a system to maximise the potential of the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">inland waterway network for the carriage of the largest and heaviest abnormal indivisible loads. </span></h2><h2 style="font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The Governments "water preferred policy” for the carriage of the largest and heaviest abnormal indivisible loads was announced on June 11th 2002 by the then P</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">arliamentary Under Secretary for Transport David Jamieson MP and clearly states that.</span></h2><h2 style="font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 24pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">"The Departments VSE Division will henceforth adopt a policy whereby water transportation is the preferred mode for the movement of the largest and heaviest abnormal indi</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">visible loads. Road movements will only be authorised where the Department has considered the possibility but believes water transportation is not feasible”</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">.</span></h2><h1 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Background &amp; Context  </span></h1><h2 style="font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">2.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The movement of the largest and heaviest AIL’s has a unique reliance on our</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> nations road transport infrastructure. Often we find ourselves seeking to push it to its limits, whether we are planning the movement of a 320 tonne electricity transformer, a 50 meter wind turbine blade or a heavy lift mobile crane, with excessive axle a</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">nd wheel loadings, but necessary for the construction of important energy infrastructure projects. </span></h2><h2 style="font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">2.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The movement of loads in excess of 150 tonnes, 6.1 meters in width and 30 meters in length are managed on behalf of the Department for Transport by the High</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ways Agency thr</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ough the “Special Order Process”.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">e are increasingly seeing examples of where the nations road transport infrastructure is not being maintained to a level that can be described as “fit for purpose”</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">.</span></h2><h2 style="font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">2.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Since the 1960s those responsible for our</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> road infrastructure have been keen to ensure that the mileage travelled by the largest and heaviest abnormal loads is minimised. In 1966 the Board of Trade funded the building and subsequent operation of two heavy load ships to facilitate the then Governm</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ents policy that large abnormal loads should be transported via the nearest appropriate port. That arrangement also encouraged the development of marine </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">infrastructure adjacent to many coastal power stations to allow these vessels to load and unload. </span></h2><h2 style="font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">2.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Whil</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">e the Government was keen to remove much of the mileage travelled by the heaviest abnormal loads</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> it also acknowledged that for many sites to be serviced there would still be a significant road movement required, and therefore the road infrastructure (more often than not to or from ports) needed to be maintained to allow passage of  these heavy loads.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span></h2><h2 style="font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">2.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">This network of road routes was to become known as the Heavy Load Grid, and the Department of Environment issued in 1972 Roads Circular 61/72 (as yet not rescinded) which highlighted the importance of maintaining the routes and acknowledged that there wo</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">uld be a financial cost to the local authorities of this but that extra cost w</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">as to be met by the Department.</span></h2><h2 style="font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">2.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The expansion of wind energy both on and off shore has contributed greatly to significant geographic reconfiguration of the UK’s power generation </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">map with wind turbines and/or associated substation infrastructure being erected across the whole country. </span></h2><h2 style="font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">2.7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">With both on and offshore wind developments there has to be a connection to the “national grid”</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> and therefore</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> we are now seeing sites being propos</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ed for on shore connections in areas of the country that have never previously seen the transportation of large electricity transmission equipment. While no problems are insurmountable</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> it is a significant challenge to find appropriate sites for substation</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> development where adequate road infrastructure exists. It should always be remembered that the logistical challenges of transporting the component parts of a single wind turbine to a site will be almost exactly the same as sites where multiple turbines ar</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">e to be erected. </span></h2><h2 style="font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">2.8.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Unfortunately we now find the heavy load grid in a state of disrepair. While most of the original road routes still exist, the ability of many of them to facilitate the movement of the largest and heaviest abnormal loads is open to questi</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">on.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The recent divestment of responsibility for maintaining the road network from central government to the Highways Agency and their “maintaining agents”</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> has clearly led to the somewhat untenable p</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">osition we now find ourselves. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">A lack of adequate and ava</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ilable archives</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> coupled with poorly written contracts are just two factors that have led to where we are now, which is that the power generation and supply industries are unable to plan with any certainty.</span></h2><h2 style="font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">2.9.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">It is imperative that steps are taken to reverse </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">the decline in the heavy load grid at a time when we are seeing the net we</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ights of electricity generation, </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">supply equipment and the size of wind turbine components rise, as generators seek to meet the ever increasing demand for electricity within prescribe</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">d environmental standards. The heavy load grid must be fit for purpose as there is a real danger that it will be the transport infrastructure that compromises the efforts to ensure that our energy needs are met over the next decade and beyond.</span></h2><h2 style="font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">2.10.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">We are encou</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">raged that the Highways Agency has indicated that it will start a process of reviewing the road routes that form part of the heavy load grid. We and many of our clients,  will be requesting that they take urgent steps to rectify some of the damage already </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">done and going forward ensure that the heavy load grid and the maintenance of it is enshrined in their contractual relationships </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">with their Maintaining  Agents.</span></h2><h2 style="font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">2.11.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">It is also imperative that any new focus on the reestablishment of the heavy load grid is mindf</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ul of the governments “water preferred policy” for the movement of the largest and heaviest abnormal load. This policy was announced in 2002 and insists that those seeking to move large loads to make best use of non-traditional ports and the UK’s commercia</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">l inland waterway network for the carriage of abnormal loads. </span></h2><h2 style="font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">2.12.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The policy has had some notable successes since its introduction, with ports such as Truro and Sharpness being used to tranship very large abnormal loads, and the rivers Thames, Ribble, Trent a</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">nd Forth being used to transport similar loads direct to power station and substation sites.  </span></h2><h2 style="font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">2.13.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The prospect for greater use of non-traditional ports, and the commercial inland waterways for the carriage and trans-shipment of large abnormal loads is very mu</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ch dependent on a joined up approach, to transport being taken by a number of stakeholders who include local authority planners, the Highways Agency, their agents, the Environment Agency and the navigation and port authorities. </span></h2><h2 style="font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">2.14.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Too often we have found tha</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">t the ability of an offloading facility whether it be coastal or on the inland waterways is compromised by a lack of joined up approach at a local level. Examples have been where suitable and historical loading/unloading sites have been developed on or acc</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ess to them has been compromised by lack of awareness. </span></h2><h2 style="font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 24pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">2.15.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The planning system can and should be used to assist with the creation of appropriate transport infrastructure. Section 106 agreements for example, are a useful way to ensure that the cost of the crea</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">tion of offloading facilities and improvements to the road network are included in the whole project cost not an afterthought when budgets have been set and in some cases spent. </span></h2><h1 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How does the Government’s policy for roads link with planning for other trans</span><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">port modes?</span></h1><h2 style="font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">3.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">One of the questions asked in the terms of reference for this inquiry is “how does the Government’s policy for roads link with planning for other transport modes”, we would say that while the “Action for Roads” document does on a number of occa</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">sions make reference to rail transport and the role it can play in reducing the burden on the road network there are very few references to coastal ports and no references to inland waterways or inland ports.</span></h2><h2 style="font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">3.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The documents also highlights the importance of</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> the promotion and facilitation of walking and cycling an increase in the take up of both will only reduce the number of cars on the road network. The promotion and facilitation of inland waterway freight transport would see the modal shift of freight from</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> the already congested trunk road network to the commercial waterways. </span></h2><h2 style="font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">3.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The movement of the largest and heaviest abnormal indivisible loads is unusual, as one of the few categories of freight whose movement is directed by Government, and while as detailed </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">previously the Government has devolved that day to day responsibility to the Highways Agency, the Government should be ensuring that there is a joined up approach to the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">implementation of its policy of minimising the road mileage travelled by the largest a</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">nd heaviest AIL’s. </span></h2><h2 style="font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">3.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">There are a number of recent examples where opportunities have been missed to develop waterside infrastructure that would have reduced the need to transport significant numbers of super heavy AIL’s throughout the life cycle of a project. This is primarily </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">due to a disjointed approach whereby those granting planning consent did not ensure that the developers have an appropriate plan in place for the transportation of the AIL’s. </span></h2><h2 style="font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 24pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">3.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">It would seem appropriate that the approvals process for issuing the Special Ord</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">er was combined with the process of gaining planning consent. Currently Special Orders only need applying for 12 weeks prior to the intended movement date, a date that is likely to be many years after planning approval is given and sometime after any plann</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ing conditions imposed by that approval are discharged. This would ensure that any increased costs of waterborne delivery (either the extra cost of infrastructure and / or of transport mode) could be considered within the total project costs rather than in</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> isolation at a later date. </span></h2><h1 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How should the Highways Agency be reformed to make it “the world’s leading highway operator”? What roles should Government and the private sector play to ensure better management of the strategic road network?</span></h1><h2 style="font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">4.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The “Action for R</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">oads” document outlines the case for the establishment of a publicly owned strategic highways company to take on the functions currently undertaken by the Highways Agency. While the case for this approach is clearly made, we are fearful that the management</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> and facilitation of the Special Order process and the movement of the largest and heaviest AIL’s may be compromised if plans to further distance responsibility for the strategic road network from the centre of Government are put in place without due consi</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">deration of the issue related to AIL movements. </span></h2><h2 style="font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 24pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">4.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">As advised previously the Highways Agency carries out a statutory function on behalf of Department for Transport as it is responsible for the on behalf of the Secretary of State for the administration of the</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> Special Order Approval process for the movement of large and heavy abnormal loads . We would wish to highlight that consideration would need to be given as to how the proposed “publicly owned strategic highways company” would carry out this function. </span></h2><h1 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Con</span><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">clusion and Recommendations </span></h1><h2 style="font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">5.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">New power generation infrastructure is crucial to ensuring a secure energy future of the UK, whether it is new nuclear, clean coal, gas or renewables. The UK strategic road network and more specifically the Heavy Load Grid has </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">a major role to play in ensuring that the power generators are able to fulfil the UK’s requirements for energy infrastructure. </span></h2><h2 style="font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">5.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">It is imperative that there is a joined up approach taken to the implementation of energy and transport policy to ensure that th</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">e UK transport infrastructure is fit for purpose. It is clear that a lack of investment and a joined up approach has compromised the heavy load grid as it is today and unless urgent steps are taken there is a real danger that the Governments plans for </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">new </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">energy infrastructure will be compromised due to a lack of suitable transport infrastructure. </span></h2><h2 style="font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">5.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The Government should take steps to ensure that the heavy load grid is re-established (considerate of the Governments water preferred policy) and appropriate arr</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">angements put in place for its maintenance and upkeep.  </span></h2><h2 style="font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">5.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The planning process should be amended to ensure that at the time of approval</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> each large scale energy development has an “agreement in principle</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">”</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> in place which details the transport route, agreed w</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ith by the Highways Agency, for the movement of the largest and heaviest abnormal indivisible loads. This route should again be considerate of the water preferred policy which maximises the opportunity for use of the inland waterway network for the carriag</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">e of the largest and heaviest AIL’s</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">.</span></h2><h1 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">October 2013</span></h1><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h1 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></h1><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>